331005;instagram;2018-09-28 13:22:53;FALSE;"i’m using this #fbf to talk about something i’ve only spoken about to a few friends and only as of recently. to my family and friends that are about to read this: i’m fine. i’ve healed on my own. please do not worry about me.

column2: i was sexually assaulted by the owner of a nightclub i worked in. i was a go-go dancer there at the time. after my first night dancing while i was counting my tips
column3: the bartender i was counting next to said
column4: “are you gonna go upstairs for drinks?” and i replied that i was tired and should probably go home. he said
column5: “really? mr. d’s boys always go upstairs for drinks after their shifts!” (his name wasn’t really mr d
column6: i just honestly don’t feel like saying his real name.)

column1: i went past the bouncer to go up to the empty bar upstairs and he gave me this weird smirk like he knew what happens up there. the bartender made me a vodka soda
column2: and the next thing i remember was waking up on the couch when the sun was starting to come out naked with my underwear around my ankles while people around me were dancing
column5: “ah! look who’s up!” i ran home mortified. i didn’t say anything then. why? because i didn’t remember every detail of the account. because i didn’t think anyone would believe me. because maybe it was my fault for trusting the strangers in the nightclub. because maybe we’d have to do a legal thing that scared me. because maybe nothing would happen. because i was embarrassed.

column2: even sharing this story now i wanna hit delete on this post. but i won’t. you wanna know why assault victims don’t come forward? because when we were in our most broken times
column3: people wouldn’t believe us. and in our strong times
column4: we’re still not convinced anyone will. it will not shock me if kavanaugh gets confirmed today because it just proves what every assault victim fears
column5: yet knows to be true. but what i will know is that we have awakened the force inside every person that has had another person hurt them. hannah gadsby said it best: “there is nothing stronger than a broken woman who has rebuilt herself.” #ibelieveher #drford #stopkavanaugh #metoo";;en;#fbf

the  power of doing life with friends 💙
inspiration and reposting this picture from kat wilson dc

over four years ago we just moved back to georgia and were looking for a local chiropractor family to support our family’s wellness. kat and i connected in a local facebook group that we both were members of because of like-minded beliefs on health and wellness.

for over four years we have gone to their house for weekly adjustments...these visits quickly became much more than keeping our spine healthy (which is a critical tool for overall wellness - research it!) - it was time for our kids to run around and create relationships and for the adults to say #metoo when it comes to parenting struggles and craziness because really we are all just trying to survive this roller coaster of parenthood.

column3: cried together and offered support and encouragement during some emotional times. this relationship has turned into deep friendships through the lord
column4: growing our tribe and business connections.

column1: we are forever grateful for this lifelong friendship that we have with you guys.

column2: abuse and scandal for the past several years. america: the jesuit review of faith & culture is the leading catholic journal of opinion in the united states. it was first published in 1909. today
column3: the editors of the review withdrew their endorsement of brett kavanaugh’s nomination to the supreme court
column4: writing: dr. christine blasey ford’s testimony before the senate judiciary committee today clearly demonstrated both the seriousness of her allegation of assault by judge brett m. kavanaugh and the stakes of this question for the whole country. judge kavanaugh denied the accusation and emphasized in his testimony that the opposition of democratic senators to his nomination and their consequent willingness to attack him was established long before dr. blasey’s allegation was known. evaluating the credibility of these competing accounts is a question about which people of good will can and do disagree. the editors of this review have no special insight into who is telling the truth. if dr. blasey’s allegation is true
column5: the assault and judge kavanaugh’s denial of it mean that he should not be seated on the u.s. supreme court. but even if the credibility of the allegation has not been established beyond a reasonable doubt and even if further investigation is warranted to determine its validity or clear judge kavanaugh’s name
column6: we recognize that this nomination is no longer in the best interests of the country. while we previously endorsed the nomination of judge kavanaugh on the basis of his legal credentials and his reputation as a committed textualist
column7: it is now clear that the nomination should be withdrawn. […]” click on @dailysoundandfury for the whole story #repost @dailysoundandfury with @get_repost

column1: 331061;instagram;2018-09-28 13:42:52;FALSE;"to find some solace after yesterday’s hearing
column2: i opened my #1 amazon bestselling book
column4: ” to this passage 🙌 perfect! it is the second book in the internationally bestselling series. so i have to believe that ultimately people want #peace or this book would not be doing so well. you can get it here: peace is power: a course in shifting reality through science and spirituality https://www.amazon.com/dp/b06xbszdtn/ref=cm_sw_r_cp_api_cpirbba8kxc7d

column1: i’m taking a short break from social media. the heartless jokes and memes about sexual assault bring me to a low vibration i don’t wish to carry. calling senators and sending post cards doesn’t seem to be helping (pretty sure they get ignored and thrown in the trash by underpaid staff)
column2: so i’m going to “work” energetically this weekend on our #rapeculture that has led to so much despair. i’m gonna focus on the ocean where i live
column4: and see the current narcissists in power covered in light
column5: because that is the truth of their souls
column6: if not their egoic personalities. i’m going to hold space for those of us in a #metoo club that we never wished to join
column7: and tap into the oneness we share in order to #rise and #unite and create a  revolutionary organizational system that overcomes the patriarchy
column9: women or men. this vile contrast has served its purpose—to wake us up and expose the truth of our pain
column10: in order to clarify what kind of world (boundaries are man-made) we do want to live in. if social media is freaking you out as it is doing to me right now
column11: i encourage you to take a “time out” as well. if not my book
column12: read something that uplifts you. go for a nature walk. listen to music. hug your family and spend quality time with friends who love and support you. peace is possible
column13: but “fighting” for it only adds to the fight. what you resist persists
column14: remember? (jung) i choose now to envision the world how i want it to be—a safe place for all to enjoy ❤️🙏🙌";;en;#1

column1: 331064;instagram;2018-09-28 13:43:10;FALSE;"it was my 23rd birthday. // i got home and laid on the floor of the shower until the water went cold. i volunteered at the dfl humphrey-mondale dinner that night and went on with my life like it was nothing. i walk past his apartment building where it happened most days. // i never said anything because i was sure it was my fault. i never said anything because i didn’t want people to think about me differently. i never said anything because i didn’t even know what to say - or who to say it to. i didn’t even know his name. // i thought about saying something when we were about to elect an admitted sexual abuser/rapist president - but i didn’t believe that could happen - so i didn’t say anything. // i thought about saying something after we elected that sexual abuser/rapist president - but it was too late anyways - so i didn’t say anything. // i’ve thought about saying something these past few days
column2: but it’s exhausting to try to put into words - never eloquent enough and never the right time. // it was my 23rd birthday. it wasn’t my fault. i’m okay. but the daily reminders are everywhere. // a sexual abuser doesn’t belong on the supreme court any more than he belongs in the white house. // thank you
column3: #christineblaseyford. your bravery and candor are inspiring and contagious. you are a true hero.

column1: 331065;instagram;2018-09-28 13:43:15;FALSE;"i’m gonna say something and it’s probably going to make some people uncomfortable. i wish i had the courage and the bravery of dr christine blesey ford. i have said this multiple times to friends and family in the last two weeks - “i would do anything to have the guts to put the two men who raped me behind bars. i hate them.” there’s a reason women don’t report. yesterday i was in awe of dr ford but i was also terrified for her
column2: i wanted to turn off the tv because i myself as a survivor was feeling attacked but if she could do the bravest thing i’ve ever seen i could be a witness to it.

column1: 331083;instagram;2018-09-28 13:30:07;FALSE;after having basically a mental breakdown yesterday from all the drama. (i believe dr. ford.) i took some time off this morning and tried not to delve into facebook politics. even though my head is killing me it is nice to know that i am loved. there is no denying happy’s love for me or just for the world in general. he wakes up most mornings playing the drums with his tale as soon as my feet hit the ground. then he plays with his big brothers all day. then about 8:30 every night he is ready to play fetch
column2: even though all the other pups are sleeping. he has such a happiness for the world and i need to really tune into that when things get tough. i had a big sigh when i started the day and i’m trying to find ways to relieve some stress and find that happiness again
column3: today is tough. hug someone today

column1: 331091;instagram;2018-09-28 13:31:00;FALSE;"i dislike being in front of the camera. maybe because i have disliked how i look for as long as i can remember. but that’s not what i want to talk about today. i rarely talk about such a serious subject as i am about to today.
i don’t live in america but i cannot help be effected by what’s been happening lately. i have been molested and sexually harassed many times in my life
column2: the earliest incident happening when i was just 7 or 8 years of age. i don’t remember much of when i was that age but i remember this incident as if it happened yesterday. and i still remember how dirty and scared i felt. just because it happened 40 years ago doesn’t make it less significant or frivolous. it has had an impact on my life. it has felt horrible and continues to feel horrible. until today i have never spoken about it. why? shame
column4: being brushed off....i don’t know. but this thread that is woven in our cultures of laughing at or blaming the woman is so tight that even at that young age i didn’t tell anyone. makes me terribly sad for the women that have gone through terrible assaults or even small incidents and didn’t feel safe enough to come forward. i hope all of you don’t take this shit anymore and step out and say “enough”! it’s more than enough. .

column1: 331092;instagram;2018-09-28 13:31:04;FALSE;"💔 so the recent events have strongly triggered many people i love to relive their past #trauma or #abuse we are all working through our traumas in our own ways but it can be so powerful to #connect with others who understand. it is also powerful to have tools at your fingertips that #support you in this process. 🌺
🌺 i want to share with you an oils protocol that really helps me deal with trauma. in this photo are the blends release
1.  release i put on the outside of my ears. it helps me feel all the feels
column2: to let things move through me and out instead of stuffing them back into my heart.

column1: 2.  valor i put on my wrists and heart. it helps me be courageous in the face of uncertainty. when my trauma pops up i feel so insecure and question my worth. valor brings my strength and worth back to the forefront where they belong.
3.  white angelica i rub between my hands
column3: and then draw a protective shield around my body. this blend is designed to protect your emotional and energetic self. how i experience it is that while i can still be emotionally available to others i don't also take on their ""stuff"". if you are like me you often find your self carrying the emotional weight of the world. white angelica helps me carry only what i need to. ✨

column1: 331093;instagram;2018-09-28 13:31:17;FALSE;"for a lot of my friends this has been a very hard week. i don’t know how to fix this broken world but i do know that i’m here for my fellow survivors and we can make it though. this week is tough but we’ve made it through worse.  tw: trauma talk
the confirmation hearings have brought up one specific unresolved trauma that’s still hard to talk about and it’s 20+ years later.

when i was about 13 my family was selected to get a habitat for humanity house  as part of receiving the house you have to contribute volunteer hours doing construction. my family trusted that we would be safe and looked out for while we worked. but on the job site i was molested (i don’t want to share specifics) by the man who was leading the project. everyone called him brother b and he was regarded as a pillar of the community. he also did the same to another family member

i still haven’t told my fam how much it actually impacted me. due to the incident my family ended up not taking the house and all that happened to brother b was a change of location. and i was stuck with trauma
column3: and a slew of intimacy issues. it’s been so many years and i still often jump when i’m touched.

column1: i was so fucked up and tired and confused. i always have to mention this because if i didn't
you asked me if i wanted this and i didn't say anything. i felt like i couldn't. i called my two best friends the morning after
column2: the morning after i drove you silently to your fucking house.
i'll admit that. i didn't want him to go to college and leave me.

column1: but that didn't give you the right to have sex with me
column3: or to fucking convince me that i wanted it.

column1: i will never forget that night; i'll never forget how you tried to justify it.

column2: telling him that one of his best friends sexually assaulted me
column3: after debating whether or not to ruin his vacation with his family.

column1: i'll never forget telling him on a bench at rocky ripple park every detail of what happened.
i'll never forget telling my dad at the picnic table in front of my work

column2: ever forget how supportive him and my dad were through all of it

column1: i didn't have sex with you.
i felt like a puppet inside my own body
column2: mindlessly watching myself until i realized what was happening and stopped it.

column3: everything brings me back to that night

column1: i'm not trying to 'ruin your life'. you made that decision when you raped me.

column1: know that if you are being triggered by recent events
column2: that you can do the following things:

column1: 1. ground yourself. find the soothing technique that works for you and brings you back to the present moment. notice your current surroundings
column2: plant your feet firmly on the ground beneath you.. 2. engage your senses. aromatherapy. peeling and eating an orange. warm bath
column3: or cooking a delicious meal are all great ways to engage all your senses.

column1: 3. reach out and talk with a trusted and supportive person who knows your story
4. be compassionate and kind to yourself

column1: 331140;instagram;2018-09-28 13:24:06;FALSE;"this has been a hard week. for me
column2: and i’m sure for all the other survivors of any kind of sexual betrayal against their body. this includes: any unwanted touches or groping
column6: rape. all the ugly words.  when i was 12 yrs old
column7: i took my moms ex-boyfriend to trial for having sexually abused me for 4 years. i told my mom what had happened one night when i was 11
column8: right away she believed me (of course) and the next day we spoke w a counselor to determine the next steps for holding him accountable. before months of therapy
column9: i had a recollection of it all going on for a year and a half
column10: and apparently that’s what i said when i first testified in grand jury before it all went to trial. long story short
column12: that mutherfucker was found not guilty on all charges. the only charge i remember was “endangering the welfare of a child”. apparently for the charge to count
column13: the abuse needed to have gone on for a minimum of 2 years. 2 years?! 2 effing years. since they went on the transcripts from grand jury
column14: what i said in my testimony for the trial didn’t matter. so
column15: he walked. karma caught up with him eventually. that’s another story though.

column2: i had sex for the first time
column4: he said “just for a minute”. i cried. it hurt. then it was over. it took me years to understand that this was rape. i didn’t fight him off but i still said “no”

column1: through adolescence there were many instances of just going along
column3: with what the guy wanted. too many.

column2: i found yoga. it was my saving grace. during this time
column3: i earned a bachelors degree in psychology. my mission was to help survivors heal.

column6: i birthed him. he weighed 9lbs 7ozs. i was in love. little did i know

column1: if your heart is brought into the light

column5: & humility be rooted in our daily actions. small
column6: incremental doses of this daily will:

column1: • change the structure of our heart
• build the foundation of our character
• help us lead the next generation to do & be better.

it’s our responsibility to change things. don’t get swept up in blaming the system or only ranting on facebook or instagram. redirect your thought a to your heart and let it convict you to make a change - no matter how small - in your life today.

you and i have been called to be the light of the world. shine that light & let others know the hope that is in the restoration & healing of jesus today. there is nothing too big or too small for our god.

column1: 331156;instagram;2018-09-28 13:11:31;TRUE;;"“the american bar association published a letter urging the senate judiciary committee to delay its vote on judge brett kavanaugh's nomination to the supreme court until the fbi conducts an investigation into the numerous sexual misconduct allegations against him
column2: according to a cnn report published thursday. ""the basic principles that underscore the senate's constitutional duty of advice and consent on federal judicial nominees require nothing less than a careful examination of the accusations and facts by the fbi
column3: aba president robert carlson said in a letter
column4: cnn reported. ""each appointment to our nation's highest court (as with all others) is simply too important to rush to a vote
column5: carlson added. ""deciding to proceed without conducting additional investigation would not only have a lasting impact on the senate's reputation
column6: but it will also negatively affect the great trust necessary for the american people to have in the supreme court."" #🍄rump

331174;instagram;2018-09-28 13:13:43;FALSE;here i am. about 14 years old in my home sitting in front of the fireplace of the kitchen i spent christmases in baking with my mom. in the home i practiced guitar
column3: and played twister with my friends during harry potter marathon nights. i was in the honor society. i studied hard. i was happy.

column1: but i was also the girl permanently traumatized by an 18-year-old boy who raped me in my sleep when i was 8. i wasn't at a party. i was in my home and as an 8 year old girl in her bed where she is supposed to feel safe
column2: i most definitely was not asking for it.

column1: when i woke up and found him on top of me
column3: i punched him in the jaw. and i found out he had been doing this to his nieces. i was the voice that spoke up and put his disgusting
column4: vile life in jail. but he didn't stay there cause that's how our government treats people like him.

column2: good. what makes me uncomfortable is the fact my trauma was written into the local newspaper forever haunting me in school as i was asked by boys in class if i was raped. what makes me uncomfortable is now living my life afraid to sleep in my own home without a knife under my pillow
column3: suffering from insomnia because if i fall asleep

column1: this continues to happen every day to other people who didn't ask for it. i don't go out and see my drunk girlfriends and say ""they're drunk. so they cause their own mess."" i get into protective mama bear mode and i make sure they get home in one piece.

column2: i believe in anyone who has the courage to share something traumatizing. it's real and it happens every single day still. and no one deserves that.

column1: 331190;instagram;2018-09-28 12:59:28;FALSE;"do you see this guy? always behind me
column2: supporting me and my crazy ideas. he rolled his eyes when i brought home a dirty
column3: broken tandem bike from a farmer’s barn sale. but he believed me when i could see the potential. he helped me fix it up and now he rides it with me. ⁣

column1: he tried to ride in front but our balance and steering was off. i’m not a very good follower - i’ve always made a good navigator. he is a quiet leader - the power in the back. so we switched seats and ride smoothly now. ⁣
who would have thought a relationship can be represented by a tandem bike? but there are a lot of similarities. i’m thankful for this man - his quiet strength and unwavering support. ⁣

column2: with the lack of belief and support and good examples of what true leadership looks like
column3: i am even more thankful for this man and his example to our son and daughter. our son has grown up to be like him and our daughter expects nothing less. ⁣

331191;instagram;2018-09-28 12:59:32;FALSE;yesterday was a hard day for many people.  survivors and those women and men who have compassion for dr. ford may still be feeling a little shell-shocked today. please be kind to yourself today if this is you. take it easy. you don’t have to watch every news broadcast
column2: you can take a walk outside
column3: you can breathe slow and easy. spend time with people who are compassionate and kind.

column1: many people do understand what it’s like to suffer sexual assault or other scary traumas that sometimes stay locked in our brains for years
column2: hidden under the surface of shame and embarrassment
column3: of uncertainty of being believed or fear of retribution or of not being supported if the truth is finally spoken aloud. it’s not easy.

column1: i have been a therapist for close to 30 years and i have worked with countless survivors. as a woman
column2: of course i have survived sexual-harassment too. when the #metoo movement came out
column3: i began to think about all the times in my life i have endured unwanted sexual comments
column5: and scary situations. my heart goes out to anyone who has suffered that and worse. i’ve had clients in my office who have never told anyone
column6: and the episodes they finally shared often happened decades earlier. there are so many reasons girls & boys
column7: women and men do not talk about sexual assault. until we stand in each other shoes we will not understand. .

column1: i am grateful for brave women like dr. ford who chose to speak up
it is our job to support survivors
column2: not shame them. it is our work to point our compasses toward safety and well-being
column4: toward freedom & growth & then even joy. it will take practice. first there is the speaking of the truth. then the rising. .

column2: if you need help and support
column3: i am happy to connect you with good resources
column4: and share what i know about the healing process. healing absolutely does happen. i know that for a fact. it does start with getting support and doing practices that calm your brain and body.  it matters what you focus on. what will you focus on today
column5: where will you point your compass? .

column2: numerous negative sensations and dark memories are surfacing as a result of the events unfolding.  while it hurts like hell
column3: i feel my heart expand to accommodate the endless stories of women (and men) that too have been the victims of sexual violence.  every female client i talked to yesterday had her own story related to power being taken away sexually by abuse or assault.  i am not surprised.  it feels dark and it should.  healing this was never gonna be easy.  it’s endemic.

column2: i can’t remember a reality devoid of the sinister capacity of men to rob innocence and joy using sex and power as tools.  i was three or four-years-old when i was first sexually violated by someone.  trauma and healing
column3: as well as the interplay and polarity between light and dark forces have been themes throughout my life as long as i can remember and surely were a survivalist construct of trauma.  as for many victims of such sexual disempowerment
column4: it has been a lifetime of deep and ugly inner work and integration to undo what’s occurred and change my story around what’s happened.  i stopped asking “why me?” awhile ago and now
column5: i ask “how do i want this story to end?” in a way
column6: i am grateful that i had to learn to lessons early and
column8: i wish i didn’t have to.  i learned to manifest joy
column9: presence and self-trust at such a young age.  trust isn’t intuitive for me
column10: as in the women i know who haven’t been robbed in the same way.  i learned to not expect a rescuer.  and
column12: i have had the privilege of getting to know myself in despair and emptiness as well as resiliency and light.  that knowledge was earned as a result of events that offered no other alternative than to heal or give up.  i will continue to listen and hold space and today and forever.  gratitude and love to #drchristineblaseyford and all survivors.  stay here and continue to #resist.  tides are turning.  #drchristineblaseyfordisahero #drchristineblaseyfordisaninspirationtousall

column1: 331216;instagram;2018-09-28 13:05:10;FALSE;"i feel the need to speak out in light of the normative dampening of the experiences of sexual assault/violence victims; especially in reference to the shitshow of a manipulated testimony by brett kavanaugh.
dr. christine blasey ford - i feel your burrowed
column2: repressed pain. i see the walls you've surrounded yourself with; the layers of claustrophobic tendencies you've used to protect yourself from the memory of your trauma. i understand your desperate need for space.

column1: i can feel the weight of my abuser's knee on my chest as you describe kavanaugh's hand covering your mouth; rediscovering my own personal strength to push a forceful 200 lb. 16 year old boy off of me in a bed i used to feel safe in.
i heard your voice as you softly spoke of someone you once thought to be your friend. although you stand here representing your truth
column2: in the back of your mind
column3: you ask yourself whether you're doing the right thing.  the idea of shaming & degrading someone in the same way they chose to do to you

column1: let me remind you that your courage to come out in spite of the threats & libel of powerful political figures has been the silver lining i'm clinging onto so desperately. that through storytelling
column2: survivors of sexual assault & violence can carry the weight of these experiences through our shared pain.

column1: this is not to say victims are not entitled to any amount of time -years even- to collect their experience; to make sense of it & find a safe time to retell their trauma on their terms. i stand in solidarity with woman & survivors today as the very integrity of our trauma remains endangered & challenged. you have a security in me for i am your friend.

this is only the beginning of collectively validating experiences of sexual assault and violence. we do not stop; we do not ever stop telling our truth. #metoo #whywouldireport #whoruntheworld #ibelieveher";;en;#MeToo

column1: 331227;instagram;2018-09-28 12:50:08;FALSE;"survivors are everywhere. i guarantee you know many more than you realize. 1 in 4 women was sexually abused before the age of 18. and 1 in 6 has survived sexual assault after the age of 18. and they carry the burden of trauma with them their whole lives.

these women are who i show up for every day. what does this have to do with makeup? my company was founded to support a non-profit that helps survivors reclaim hope and find healing. that’s the whole reason we exist. every time you support me in any way
know that i am always a safe place. reach out anytime. and if you’d like online resources or to apply for a free healing retreat
and as a mother of daughters
column2: i am doing my best to teach and protect them. parents and caregivers
column3: you will find free resources at @defendinnocence for starting age-appropriate conversations that matter.

column1: 331273;instagram;2018-09-28 12:42:09;FALSE;"three years ago today my interview with elle uk magazine came out.
it was both terrifying and such an honor to have been one of 3 women around the world selected to share my story about what shaped me as a woman
column2: and my idea of femininity and womanhood.

column1: picture 1: cover of magazine and excerpts from my interview.
picture 2: with a bit of anxiety
column2: here is a screenshot of my part of the article : (there were 2 other women interviewed: one is the 1st transgender model signed by a global agency and is based out of nyc
column3: the other is an economist and self-proclaimed tomboy based in paris....and then there's me...just a girl from wi...) the interview is heavy
column4: especially if you don't know me. i'm not sure if my views on womanhood
column5: identity and femininity are stated within my words
column6: but maybe they are implied through the story and the way i live my life. either way

column1: a few months ago i received a message that a woman wanted to interview me for a magazine about womanhood
column2: identity and femininity. she had heard the story about my mother and specifically sought me out to see how that shaped my views as i grew into my own woman.

column1: that woman was @loustoppard and that magazine was @elleuk .

column2: reading the stories of the other women
column3: and then reading my own. my first thoughts are how uninteresting and unaccomplished and uninspiring i am.....why do we do that to ourselves?

column1: then i really sat back and thought about each of my words
column2: and all of the memories and life lessons attached to them. i have made mistakes
column4: but i have grown into a very resilent and independent woman with the most sentimental of hearts.

column1: i hope every person is able to find that feeling within themsleves. it is empowering.
be honest. be kind.  be healthy. be confident.  be you.

column1: 331283;instagram;2018-09-28 12:43:21;FALSE;"i don’t get political on my social media. one
column2: because i’ve been frightened of how my views might make other people “feel” about me. two
column3: it makes you vulnerable to the attacks of those who don’t think the same
column5: i’ve never been “brave” enough. that changes now. yesterday was hard. not just to watch but to process and digest. but
column6: someone very important told me to give myself the gift of confidence this year for my birthday and so i am working on doing that. part of that is sticking up for myself and for what i think is good. i want to have faith that goodness will prevail. but
column7: most importantly- i want to make sure that my voice is heard. for all of the mothers
column12: friends- i want to say you matter now and always.

column2: courage requires vulnerability. took time to get myself up to speed in the news world with the kavanaugh case  this morning. to be honest
column3: i tend to avoid the news because it can be depressing af at times 🙄. at the same time
column4: i choose to be a part of change for the greater good of this world. what can i say? i feel sad. not necessarily for one thing over an other
column5: but mostly that people can be so attacking to someone that is reporting a sexual assault. as i reflect on the wild shift in women speaking up over the past few years
column6: i think of myself and how many times i’ve minimized my own experiences to fit in with the norm of society. i think of the insane amount of courage it has taken these women to not stay silent and come forward
column7: and still-how these women are seen and treated. it’s always been understandable for me as to why my clients and other people in my life do not report or say anything about sexual assault. the reality is
column8: more times than not in our society
column9: not only will you not be believed
column10: but you will be ridiculed and punished. when i say this now
column11: i’m not speaking solely in regard to dr. ford
column12: i’m speaking to the stories i’ve been told in the countless number of traumatized women i have come to know and work with in my career. as much as it saddens me to see the state our beautiful country is in
column13: it equally motivates me to stand in courage and speak up. to support those who are so bravely reaching out and sharing their story. no matter who you are or what you have or haven’t been through
column14: know that you’re a part of this planet and for that reason we are all connected. even if you think these issues have nothing to do with you
column15: you are mistaken. start conversation with the women in your life and see what they have to say about sexual assault. you may be surprised
column16: saddened or sickened to hear what your friends

column2: i believed the sexual abuse i experienced as a child caused me to be gay. i believed that i had little worth and that i would be forever damaged. i believed god had cursed me
column4: and that i could never be happy.

column1: i was abused between the ages of five and eight by a teenage boy. i turn 40 this year and i still struggle with the impact of that abuse. i didn’t tell anyone for years
column2: because i was afraid/ashamed/ embarrassed/didn’t want to hurt anyone/didn’t know how/didn’t know if anyone would believe me.

column1: healing has taken years. today i am confident and happy. i’m in a healthy relationship. i am fiercely protective of my children. i know now that being gay wasn’t a result of the abuse. and i also recognize that the abuse hurt me in ways i may never understand or fully realize. i still get nervous and angry when i see my abuser
column2: someone i try to avoid but always can’t. he’s never taken accountability.

column1: healing from sexual abuse takes a lifetime. survivors deserve kindness
column4: and to be believed. yesterday’s senate trials challenged me in ways i couldn’t have anticipated
column5: triggering my own past traumas. i work with the survivors of assault and abuse as a therapist on a regular basis
column6: and they are almost overwhelmingly women who have been hurt by men
column7: and some men who have been hurt by men.

column1: i stand with all of the survivors out there in sharing my story with bravery. it’s time for a new and better world. i rise today with confidence and self care and continue to work on a better and healthier me.

column1: 331301;instagram;2018-09-28 12:30:13;FALSE;"i believe it’s important to keep controversy out of your business’s social media campaign- unless your job calls for it.  but after the events of yesterday
column2: i think we are all processing.  i believe her.  we all have men in our lives that we love and at the same time
column3: have female friends that we stand by and believe as they tell us their stories and experiences of assault.  it is not a right of passage for young men to assault women.  yesterday has been another reminder to take that friend’s hand and listen as she tells you her pain.  to reach out to that girl and tell her you have time for her.  and yesterday was also a reminder to say your peace on election day. .

column2: i listened to dr. christine blasey ford’s testimony of abuse. she was nervous and seemed very uncomfortable. she also admitted to not remembering everything
column3: but she also explained in scientific terms how she was able to remember specific sounds and feelings due to storage in the hippocampus of her brain. i believe her.

column1: of course this wasn’t enough for some people. a so-called christian correspondent on fox news likened her testimony to potiphar’s wife who tried to seduce joseph in ancient egypt. it was bizarre—like comparing applesauce to orange juice
column2: but this has often been the burden for every woman who tells her story of abuse. and a good reason why people wait years to tell their stories.

column1: women are often put on trial
column2: while their male perpetrators often play the role of a victim. we saw this yesterday. someone asked why no one questioned the men who recently reported an abusive priest? men who report abuse are not subjected to the ridicule and accusations that dr. ford was. why is it so easy to believe a man and not a woman?

column1: many people in the room believed her
column2: but they don’t care if she is telling the truth—they have an agenda and accusing her of lies is just another means to an end. such false representatives of the people need to be voted out. there is also no one more heartless and cruel than a woman who turns on another woman for telling her story.

column1: meanwhile dr. christine blasy ford stands tall in her truth and reminds us that all of our stories matter. even those stored in the hippocampus for thirty-five years. women all over the world are taking courage because she spoke her truth. this is what freedom looks like. the alternative is to hide in the background and allow more sad stories to happen. you have stories too—some are better than others
column3: don’t let the narcissist intimidate you into silence. use your freedom to set yourself and others free.

column1: so the reason i’m bringing this up is because i wanted to offer support to those who are being triggered by the hearings. so many people who have been sexually assaulted
column2: abused or had unwanted sexual contact are now undergoing post traumatic stress from these hearings. many are reliving their own assaults and having difficulty as many news stations are blaming the victim. i would avoid watching clips as it’s difficult to digest if you are an abuse survivor.
their pain is a result of their abuse
column3: and triggers like the current hearings may cause flares in pain. if you or someone you know is a victim please reach out to your support team whether it’s yours doctor

column1: 331400;instagram;2018-09-28 11:45:29;FALSE;"@foxnews contributor #kevinjackson was fired thursday after calling the three women who have publicly accused supreme court justice nominee #brettkavanaugh of sexual misconduct “lying skanks.”.
“kevin jackson has been terminated as a contributor
column2: ” a fox spokesperson said in a statement. “his comments on today’s hearings were reprehensible and do not reflect the values of fox news.”

column1: jackson was tweeting during the senate judiciary committee hearing in which professor christine blasey ford testifiedthat kavanaugh assaulted her in the 1980s during a high school house party. ford testified that kavanaugh held her down and grinded on her as he tried to take off her one piece bathing suit.

column4: they want men to never be believed. i’m not succumbing. to hell with the notion women must be believed no matter what. lying skanks is what these three women are

column1: a week after ford stepped forward with her account of assault
column2: deborah ramirez claimed that kavanaugh exposed himselfin front of her during a college party. on wednesday
column3: a third accuser named julie swetnick came forward with claims that she witnessed him “consistently engage in excessive drinking and inappropriate contact of a sexual nature with women in the early 1980s.”

column1: kavanaugh swiftly denied all three allegations.

column1: 331413;instagram;2018-09-28 11:49:44;FALSE;"do i remember every detail? perhaps not
column4: a man lured me and a friend away. sat us down instilling fear. told us what his experience in prison was like. he then locked us in separate rooms. i was terrified. i wet my pants. he took a pistol and placed it up and down my inner thigh along with his erect penis. he then went into the room my friend was locked in. i thought if i escaped out the window he may kill her and i wasn’t sure if i could live with that. he entered back into the room
column5: zipping up his pants. as the experience continued i was able to convince him to let us free. i employed tactics of direct and precise statements with calmness. i needed to get us safe. after telling the authorities
column6: we were taken to norhridge hospital in california for stressful questioning and a pelvic exam to be performed to support the documented case. “you know
column7: sometimes kids lie or exaggerate the truth.” these words i heard from outside the hospital room. it would continue on to the judicial system where the punishment given was not to come within 100 yards from me. yes
column8: a man with a criminal record was given a slap on the wrist for sexually assaulting a 12 year old girl. so why you ask don’t more come forward? often because of examples like mine. no more! enough! #timesup ~alisa k ▪️▪️▪️▪️▪️

column1: i became i what i needed in order to be what you need because
i thought i could save you.
i didn’t have the strength on my own to continue living in that pain.
i had nothing left to give but god gave me you and i wanted you to live your best life so i decided to show you you could dream out loud.
the journey to the love i wanted to be for you gave me strength and a big voice to protect you with.
the journey gave me the experience to nurture you with.
the journey gave me all the tools that i could give to you but it also taught me there is no cape or crown i can dawn that will protect you from every evil in the world.
the tools give you the ability to triumph.
you need a why that makes the turmoil before the triumph mean enough to press on.
i pray that you have a why that compels you as much as the love i have for you.
i pray your why fuels you when darkness tries to consume you.
i pray your why compels you to be more for others when you start to feel you might not have the strength to press on for yourself.
i pray that in these times
you remember you are filled with light and only that can dispel the dark.
shine your light with all your might
column2: and be the love you wish to see.

column1: those who see you recognize that their light also shines in you.
this is what i mean when i say ✨💙👑

column1: at the top of my list of greatest horrors is men who hurt women and get away with it. i
column3: have had to see our greatest horror play out over and over again on the political stage of the most powerful nation in the world
column4: in ways such as but not limited to trump’s presidency and the kavanaugh hearing. in recent years
column5: i frequently discuss the strength and power of the female body
column6: but too many times in the past
column7: terrible men have succeeded in momentarily claiming my body and life as theirs despite my vehement struggle to prevent it. here’s my story. 1: in paris
column9: jilted long-term partner was of the attitude that he deserved intercourse. i supposed to vengefully make up for the times he thought he should have gotten it
column10: he got inside my building and forced himself on me repeatedly as i screamed and struggled. #drchristineblaseyford speaks of the uproarious laughter of the men who satisfied themselves with her body without her consent
column12: as the memory seared most strongly in her mind
column13: and i concur—the power trip scares me as much as the physical violation does. 2: i have four international warrants against another ex-partner who tried to physically prevent me from leaving toronto where i was visiting and broke up with him because he was literally shouting abuse
column14: and stalked me across both new york and paris over the course of two years—e.g.
column15: literally staking me out in east campus at columbia
column16: them posing as my long-distance boyfriend at columbia’s paris campus at reid hall to try and charm the staff into releasing my address. he saw that i had signed up for a wine tasting as part of the study abroad programming on a sheet on the wall
column17: and wrote down the time and address to intercept me there. i’ll spare you the additional details. i hope that some of you on the fence will choose to #believesurvivors in your everyday life and on the national stage
column18: because our lives and wellbeing depend on it.";;en;#DrChristineBlaseyFord

column1: 331500;instagram;2018-09-28 11:22:39;FALSE;"thanks to @americanwitch13 for this great meme. tw: discussion of sexual assault

column2: whose experience shared many similar details to dr. ford's
column3: the current news cycle has been incredibly difficult for me. i try to find humor where i can
column4: to try and throw the rage
column7: and sense of helplessless out of my body for a bit to get a break. i've been filled with violent fantasies of vengeance and retribution that feel as much like poison inside me as they feel righteous. #whyididntreport my abuser was very rich and respected
column8: whereas my family was very poor. we would have never had the money for representation to pursue a case. plus
column9: i was underage and drinking when it happened
column10: and due to the whims of asshole kids i'd had an (undeserved) reputation as a slut since the age of 11. no one in law enforcement would have ever believed me. and the fact that all of this was running through my head as i was pinned down and struggling is what is the most tragic part. i truly hope that one day we can live in a world that is fair and just. where the system isn't rigged against anyone is not not rich
column12: and male. until then i pray the #metoo movement makes everyone think twice before they act
column13: and that survivors continue to feel increasingly emboldened to come forward

column1: 331501;instagram;2018-09-28 11:23:01;TRUE;;"repost by guardian:  eleven days after stepping forward to accuse brett kavanaugh of sexual assault
column2: dr christine blasey ford walked in to dirksen senate office building prepared to relive a moment that she said “drastically altered” her life.

column1: the senators – 17 men and only four women – sat facing her in rapt attention. ford described what she said was a traumatic assault in the summer of 1982. she said a heavily intoxicated kavanaugh and his friend

column1: 331535;instagram;2018-09-28 11:05:20;FALSE;"i believe dr. ford.  i have been trying to figure out why i have felt so emotionally drained for the past few days...and i realized that it’s watching the world tell me that women are still simply not important and it’s ok for guys to violate whoever they want as long as it’s behind closed doors where no one sees. and as a victim of sexual assault myself this makes me feel small and worthless.
and for everyone shouting “where is the evidence” ..... he is not on trial! it’s a glorified job interview!! and even if he doesn’t get this job then he will still be a judge!! his life is not ruined
column2: no one is trying to send him to jail
column3: but the people nominated to the supreme court for life should be above reproach! this is not a position you simply say oh you’re good enough for
column4: you need to be the freakin best. and if three women contacted a company you owned that was hiring saying a man sexually harassed or assaulted them you probably would hire someone else too. it’s not a trial it’s a testament of moral character. and honestly if a women responded the way he did yesterday to similar questions at a job interview then she would be called hysterical and never hired...but the disgusting part of this whole thing is the senate is gonna confirm this guy no matter how many women come forward because apparently women simply don’t matter...still. ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀

column1: 331555;instagram;2018-09-28 10:32:29;FALSE;"it happened to #metoo. i cried yesterday listening to the giant #drchristineblaseyford who bravely and in service to her country and women everywhere went through the gruelling process publicly of talking about a long ago sexual assault.
thank you for your bravery. thank you for the price you and your family have paid personally for your courage and candour.

column2: the thing that remains for me is the acknowledgment of being treated as if not human for someone else’s violent pleasure and moreover
column3: the denigration of what was a violent act with shame after it was made into a joke at my expense.

column1: like you #drchristineblaseyford it was inside my social group. like you it took decades for me to actually own what had happened and put words to it. like you #drchristineblaseyford it still is shameful and upsetting. but because of you #drchristineblaseyford more girls and women will understand and have words if it happens to them and know it can happen to anyone. and the shame should be at the feet of perpetrators. #ibelievechristineblaseyford #ibelievesurvivors";;en;#metoo.

column4: in the us most high school sex ed classes do not focus on this type of education but more abstinence and human anatomy. i’m by no means saying these are bad principles in theory
column5: but by not understanding consent we end up here. so how can we start addressing this epidemic? in sweden
column6: they start teaching children in kindergarten what it means to consent. not convos about sex of course
column7: but asking if someone would like a hug and if someone says no they respect their space
column8: this is a fantastic first step that starts ingraining a positive message in the youth that 1. it’s okay to say no and 2. that if they hear no it’s also okay. i’m sure everyone has encouraged their child

column1: i stand with her. i am her. i was the girl who never reported because i blamed myself. i was the woman who never reported because i didn’t want to go through the pain and ridicule. the same sort of pain that i witnessed dr christine blasey ford walk through today. what we saw today is about a much bigger issue of survivors of sexual assault being persecuted
column2: judged and re-traumatized when they do come forward. we are told that if it were “real”
column3: we would have reported it at the time. often when we were merely children or young girls. girls who were assaulted and then had “whore” written on lockers because rumors spread. girls who were afraid of becoming a pariah in their social circles because they told the truth. it was easier to stay quiet. and as we grew older and it happened again
column4: we had been trained to remain silent. we had learned the lesson that no one will believe us. that even if someone does
column5: it holds no consequence. we had watched other women come forward
column6: only to be told “there were no witnesses
column7: so it’s your word against his”
column8: knowing that “his” story is always more believed than “hers”. this isn’t about politics for me. this is about a panel of people brushing aside someone’s trauma. i will not sit still. i will not stay quiet. although i may never be as brave or as unflinching in the face of such an inquisition as she was today
column9: it has given me hope. that maybe
column11: female survivors of sexual assault may be heard. even if our voice is barely above a whisper. #imwithher #listentoyourwomen #tellyourtruth #ihearyou";en;#metoo

column1: 331590;instagram;2018-09-28 10:01:04;FALSE;"喜愛攝影的朋友們，多少都有拍攝人像的經驗。然而，不論是攝影師或模特兒，在攝製過程中或影像完成後，腦中可能都曾閃過一些疑問與擔憂。我們發現，在雙方對彼此的基本權益與合作關係，皆不確定的情形下，很容易導致糾紛。
有感於此，lightbox 決定延續今年7月「＃metoo運動與當代攝影」的討論會，在「台灣當代一年展」期間，舉辦一場座談。主題聚焦於攝影師、模特兒在合作時可能會遭遇到的各類問題，並邀請法律、性別議題工作者前來分享專業觀點，提供可能的解方。
其中，在「法律百科」的協力下，鑽研著作權法的李佩昌律師，擬訂了一份攝影師與模特兒的「合作參考本」（類似定型化契約）。並將於講座中向聽眾介紹這份參考本的使用方式，釐清肖像權、著作權的相關問題。而長期關注性別議題的郭怡青律師，則將從性別的角度分析相關拍攝爭議，並與大家分享性別領域的法律知識。
10月6日下午2點，歡迎所有的影像創作者、被攝影愛好者，或對勞動權益、性別議題有興趣的朋友們，一起來參與這次的座談。聆聽法律人的觀點，也提供自身的經驗與意見，共同來為台灣攝影社群的勞動環境、性別意識盡一份心力，轉化為提升勞權、性別意識的養分。 ——————————————————
📍 台北花博公園爭豔館 大會主舞台
🗣 李佩昌（六合法律事務所律師）
🗣 郭怡青（婦女新知基金會董事、律師）
🏃🏻 自由入場（免報名、免付費）

🏃🏻 自由入場（免報名、免付費）

——————————————————";喜愛攝影的朋友們，多少都有拍攝人像的經驗。然而，不論是攝影師或模特兒，在攝製過程中或影像完成後，腦中可能都曾閃過一些疑問與擔憂。我們發現，在雙方對彼此的基本權益與合作關係，皆不確定的情形下，很容易導致糾紛。 有感於此，lightbox 決定延續今年7月「＃metoo運動與當代攝影」的討論會，在「台灣當代一年展」期間，舉辦一場座談。主題聚焦於攝影師、模特兒在合作時可能會遭遇到的各類問題，並邀請法律、性別議題工作者前來分享專業觀點，提供可能的解方。 其中，在「法律百科」的協力下，鑽研著作權法的李佩昌律師，擬訂了一份攝影師與模特兒的「合作參考本」（類似定型化契約）。並將於講座中向聽眾介紹這份參考本的使用方式，釐清肖像權、著作權的相關問題。而長期關注性別議題的郭怡青律師，則將從性別的角度分析相關拍攝爭議，並與大家分享性別領域的法律知識。 10月6日下午2點，歡迎所有的影像創作者、被攝影愛好者，或對勞動權益、性別議題有興趣的朋友們，一起來參與這次的座談。聆聽法律人的觀點，也提供自身的經驗與意見，共同來為台灣攝影社群的勞動環境、性別意識盡一份心力，轉化為提升勞權、性別意識的養分。 —————————————————— 🕑 10/6（六）14:00-15:30 📍 台北花博公園爭豔館 大會主舞台 🗣 李佩昌（六合法律事務所律師） 🗣 郭怡青（婦女新知基金會董事、律師） 🏃🏻 自由入場（免報名、免付費） 💬 slido 06 —————————————————— ;[('喜愛攝影的朋友們，多少都有拍攝人像的經驗。然而，不論是攝影師或模特兒，在攝製過程中或影像完成後，腦中可能都曾閃過一些疑問與擔憂。我們發現，在雙方對彼此的基本權益與合作關係，皆不確定的情形下，很容易導致糾紛。'

column1: 331618;instagram;2018-09-26 18:34:32;FALSE;"today’s news is making me really sick so i’m revisiting this handmade accordion book i made for my hysteria project (link in my bio) about sexism and gender disparities in healthcare
column3: and industry and how that can be witnessed through the story of hormonal birth control. it’s a deeply personal story that i am still trying to figure out how to frame and how best to present but i made this little book using prints from my go-to lab @socialps (these are their 5”x5” classic matte prints) bound simply with book binding tape. my hands are shaking hearing these latest allegations against #brettkavanaugh and hearing how quickly people are attacking the women coming forward. sexual assault is not a partisan issue! gang rape is just not okay. and a nominee to the supreme court of all people should be calling for a proper legal investigation into these claims. look at how these women are being treated and then ask yourself why women don’t speak up sooner
column4: or why they don’t go to the police. now i’m going to get back to painting my house because home is my safe haven
column5: it is the place i can escape the inequities of the world and feel secure.

column3: for a very long time. i kept my grief and shame hidden deliberately away
column4: and waited for moments alone in the shower or car or woods to give myself the chance to feel the enormity of what happened without explanation or judgment. i couldn’t believe it had happened to me. i was so fucking ashamed and i internalized every ounce of it
column5: to the point where i would take cigarettes and lighters and burn myself
column6: hoping to feel pain but not the kind i was actually stuck in. i didn’t know who to go to; i couldn’t even formulate the words in my head to start a conversation with my family about what had happened. i just picked it up
column7: jammed it into my bag of shitty life experiences
column8: and started carrying that baggage down the road.

column1: eventually i shared that i had been assaulted with my family
column3: and a handful of trusted friends. i only did so because my best friend begged me to
column4: because she said it was destroying me and i needed to let it out. she was right. i stuck that part of myself that i was so embarrassed and ashamed of
column5: that i was so mad at for being so stupid to be so vulnerable
column6: into the shadows and it was threatening now to pull the whole of me in with it. shining a light onto what we’ve been masking is terrifying
column7: but the first step in reclaiming our self.

column1: i’ve pretty much always been known for being outspoken and honest and a feminist. and i hid this god awful thing
column2: convinced it would be better tucked away from any inconvenience it might cause anyone
column3: disillusioned that it would all disappear if only properly ignored. what dr. ford did yesterday broke me and set me into flight all at once. her bravery
column4: because she must have been terrified to testify
column5: had me crying tears of mourning
column6: for myself and all the other survivors. she had me in tears of rage as social media helped to reveal how many of us silent survivors there are. she had me in tears of determination that my daughters will not know this trauma and my son won’t be part of this cycle. 🔻.

column1: if you feel like you are wearing your organs on the outside of your body right now. if you have been crying along with christine because her story is your story. if you can barely breathe and your chest feels like it is going to burst as her memories are your memories and the memories of all of the women who came before us.
if it is helpful - post a word
column3: or any kind of sharing about how you are feeling right now. we can respond to each other with love. not to cover over or to fix but to hold tender space in solidarity that all of your emotions are right now wrong.

column1: tears are water and water erodes resistance. only robots and us “presidents” elected in 2017 don’t cry.

my favorite metaphor from 2017 is that we are a chorus. and when we sing in choruses we have to stagger our breathing because we all need breaks to keep going. if you need to stagger your breathing today i hope you do. i hope you turn it all off if that is what will be the most nourishing path for you.
i stand with and believe christine

column1: 331679;instagram;2018-09-28 08:58:23;FALSE;"still here. still showing up. still providing for my loved ones. still holding space for those who need it.

column2: #ibelieveher. i'm so tired of this narrative. there are no excuses for the ""why don't victims report it"" line of thought. none. there are literally millions of stories that survivors post
column3: tweet and talk about every day - sacrificing so much of their energy
column6: income and privacy to do - there can be no more excuses for choosing to not listen.

column1: i share my own stories openly
column2: not for validation or to ""convince people to believe"" because frankly
column3: fuck them. but so that the thousands of people who read/hear my stuff see that it's possible to experience and expose the most horrific violations - and remain shame-free
column5: spiritually and physically on fleek and to use an outdated term
column6: 'pure'. you can be happy and full of rage at the #patriarchy & #machismo.

column2: they said i was asking for it.
they said it was easier to fire me.
they said i was just wanting attention.
they said i was lying to extort money.
they said it would ruin his career.
they said i should have stopped it.

column1: 331680;instagram;2018-09-28 08:58:59;FALSE;"i will always stand with survivors. the biggest fear for me when i first shared my story of rape was whether i would be believed. but why would i make it up?! there are so many reasons why people who have experienced rape/sexual assault keep quiet and unless you’ve ever been in that situation i realise it may be hard to understand why.
the very nature of the trauma makes your mind shut it out
column2: pretend it hasn’t happened and numb out any feelings.

column1: the shame and guilt for me were huge too
column2: thinking incorrectly that i had brought it on myself because i had been drinking and stayed in an empty flat.

column1: then i had denial and minimisation and didn’t call it rape for years.

column2: leaving my body when the violence escalated
column3: watching what was happening from on top of the wardrobe to the young 13 year old down below

column1: one of the last things my rapists said to me as they held the knife against my throat (a knife they had already used on me) was that if i told anyone that they would kill me. i believed them
all of these feelings (i haven’t even mentioned my many phobias
column7: alcohol etc) were compounded by the many victim blaming messages we are fed by the rape  culture that was present back then in the late 1970’s and is still so strong now!

column1: and you still wonder why it takes so long for survivors to find their voice!

column1: i was 7 years old living with my mother and younger sister in costa rica. my mother loved to party and get wild when she separated from my adoptive father. she would bring different men in the our home. she was dating this one guy
column3: he told my mother he was a doctor. so when it came to our well being
column4: he would check us all the time. question
column5: is it normal to check a 7 and 2 years old vagina? oh no
column6: okay that’s what i thought. this was the start of my sexual abuse. my mother and h grew in their relationship. he had moved in and my mother felt comfortable enough to let him watch us
column7: her two little girls. i never felt confortable with this man and my mother forced me to hug him and kiss him goodnight and treat him like a father figure. one day
column8: my mother and baby sister had to make the trip back to the us to visit my adoptive father and had h watch me while they were away. my nanny was given the weekend off and i was stuck with this man. i remember him cooking me dinner one night and eating it. then everything went foggy and somehow the next morning i woke up in my nightgown with blood between my legs. i didn’t understood what happened and i thought i was dying. i got up and went to the bathroom. i felt extremely sore inside me and i felt extreme pain. i got in the shower and scrubbed myself raw until my skin was red. i cried until i was numb and felt dead inside in that shower. i lost everything of my childhood that day. after mother got back from the us
column9: h left my mother. she was devastated and didn’t understand why he left. after about 2 weeks from their break-up
column10: i went up to my mother and told her what i remember happened that day and what happened the next day. i will never forget the anger and disgust on her face. her exact words to me were “you fucking whore
column11: you caused this!” i kept silent for so long and i felt dead inside after this moment. i never wanted to die more than that day that i told my mother. i never spoke about it ever again to anyone. not even my adoptive father. all i knew was that
column12: i was never going to be love and i never will be able trust anyone ever in my life. column2: but she was so scared. he held her down. she lay there barely able to move. she remembers the feeling of her tears falling from her eyes
column3: welling in a pool in her ears and then drenching her hair so vividly that she can’t ever lay crying in that position even now

column1: she felt to blame. she felt shame. she wondered if she had done enough. she wondered if she could have done more to stop it. she also chose to stay with him. because of all of these reasons
sometimes she thinks about that girl and wishes she had been stronger. other times she’s proud of her bravery. most of all she’s just glad she survived and is here to tell the story.
she is me. i am her. this is me. this is my truth. i am brave.
thank you 🙏🏽 @off.the.rocks @kristinlabak and @alys_wickedsober for sharing your stories today. it inspired me to write this down and get it out. it helped. thank you 💗

column1: i have been sexually assaulted too many times to count.
first as a young child 7 or 8 by some family friends who tried to grab me where they shouldn't. this happened often. sometimes they succeeded.
then when i was about ten an older boy (about 6 years older)
column3: he took me to the grocery store and assaulted me in the car on the way back.

column1: then in the uk walking out of the tube two men walked by me and grabbed my ass as i walked by.
last year at an acro jam a cheer coach walked up behind me while i was holding my daughter and put his hand between my legs and picked me up. we weren't doing a trick; he did not have my consent.
i have survived all of these incidents with my dignity intact but nothing prepared me for what my child told me when i came home last year. she also has a story and it was her own father.
and my scars split open and my heart began to bleed. my soul lost in a pit of despair as agencies and adults covered up the word of a child. they dont believe the child
column2: they say mommy made it up. i am still fighting the system. we will not be silent or go away. she told many adults!!! to the abuser and his father who still stalk me on social media these days. your time is up. i will not stop seeking truth. the evidence will show what you have done. i will not stop until her voice is heard.

column1: 331823;instagram;2018-09-28 10:14:29;FALSE;"i gotta say i couldn’t be disappointed with humanity then i am at this moment. i just....i honestly don’t even know the words to explain how much what’s happening in the world hurts my heart. what are we teaching our kids? what kind of world are they going to be coming into? what kind of fucking messes are we leaving behind for them to clean up!? what message are we sending to these little humans?! this needs to stop 🛑 .

it sickens me to see so many hash tags. #imwithher #metoo #hatehasnohomehere #blacklivesmatter #transrights now just to clarify my support is with each one of them...but it saddens me that these things aren’t already supported...by everyone!!’ at this point it doesn’t matter why or how we got on one side or the other. all that matters is that we get on the same side. .

shame on anyone who questions a woman who has the balls to come forward about any type of sexual assault. shame on you for disliking someone because they believe in a different god then you. shame on you for judging someone based on their sexuality or their identifying gender. shame on you for turning your nose up to someone because they don’t wear expensive clothes or drive an expensive car. humanity needs us.  we are all the same. we all hurt the same

column1: @regran_ed from @guardian -  eleven days after stepping forward to accuse brett kavanaugh of sexual assault
column2: dr christine blasey ford walked in to dirksen senate office building prepared to relive a moment that she said “drastically altered” her life.

column1: the senators – 17 men and only four women – sat facing her in rapt attention. ford described what she said was a traumatic assault in the summer of 1982. she said a heavily intoxicated kavanaugh and his friend
column3: locked her in a room during a small house party in maryland. she said kavanaugh started to grind his body against hers as he tried to remove her clothing. when she tried to scream
column4: she said he put his hand over her mouth to silence her. judge said he doesn't recall the incident. whatever the outcome of the hearings
column5: kavanaugh’s nomination has undeniably inflamed a deep cultural divide in today’s #metoo era of reckoning on sexual assault and harassment. ______________________________________________________

column2: images of gentleness and softness may be what first comes to mind. but there is another side to self-compassion which is fierce and strong and is every bit as important. 💪🏽
leading researcher in the field of self-compassion describes these two sides as the “yin and yang of self-compassion.” the yin is the tender
column3: gentle side that aims to comfort and soothe our pain
column4: whereas the yang is the part we tap into to protect ourselves or provide for others. in the course i attended earlier this year neff compared it to being a “mama bear” protecting her children (or inner child). she connected it to the compassion towards self and others that we see in social justice movements and more specifically to the #metoo movement. i had this on my mind yesterday when in the u.s. we witnessed one woman’s very brave
column5: public display of yang compassion towards her country and her self. over the past year i’ve seen more and more women (both in my personal life and clients) showing their own displays of yang self-compassion and saying “i love myself too much to continue to carry this secret and shame. it is not ok that i was treated in this way. it is not ok that this continues to be part of our culture.” these are times of intense mixed emotions—uncomfortable ones like anger
column8: and grief but also of hope and inspiration at the display of women demonstrating their fierceness and strength. 💕 .

column1: your own display of yang self-compassion doesn’t need to be grand or even overly public. you can begin to practice it in small ways that feel safer right now. it can be saying no to plans this weekend because you need to recharge your batteries. or telling your inner critic “it is not ok to speak to me that way
column2: i deserve more.” wishing you a weekend full of moments to let your own mama bear show! 🐻 💪🏻 #femaleempowerment #whorulestheworldgirls #expatwomen

column1: 331907;instagram;2018-09-28 11:14:37;FALSE;"yesterday was heavy. today is heavy. many of us were triggered and reminded of our personal experiences with sexual assault and lines being crossed
column2: including me. i’ve never stopped to fully process how commonplace it is for us to have our guards up until i stopped to fully process it. as women we’ve been taught to always be aware of our surroundings
column4: be ready to kick and scream in the event a man decides to attack us. we’ve carried our keys sticking out through our fingers when walking to our cars. we’ve left one headphone off while on a solo hike or run. we’ve kept our heads up and eyes scanning the scene when out after dark
column5: or any time of day for that matter. we’ve had pepper spray in our hands or attached to our key chains. we’ve held tight to our drinks in a public place. we’ve been taught to change our behaviors because there are men who cannot control themselves
column6: the burden falls on us. we’ve spent our days living with fear disguised as normalcy. this is not normal.

column5: or any time of day for that matter. we’ve had pepper spray in our hands or attached to our key chains. we’ve held tight to our drinks in a public place. we’ve been taught to change our behaviors because there are men who cannot control themselves
column6: the burden falls on us. we’ve spent our days living with fear disguised as normalcy. this is not normal.

column1: #metoo being proven unworthy of a seat on the highest court in the nation is not “ruining someone’s life.” (especially when you have no remarkable qualifications whatsoever besides being a conservative and going on record saying that a current president should not be subject to investigation). a few things that do threaten to ruin people’s lives are: time spent away from your job while you go through the process of trying to press charges against your rapist
column2: money spent on therapy bills that should really be going toward rent
column3: involuntary ptsd symptoms invading new relationships you care about
column4: not being able to drive past certain buildings without shaking
column5: lingering feelings of shame and unworthiness that are constantly being reinforced by inconsiderate talking heads who care more about their own agenda than the actual suffering caused by men so bloated by their privilege that they can’t even comprehend others’ pain—a trait
column7: fairly integral to being a judge. hold public officials to impeccable standards of morality and skill. few members of the executive branch meet these standards. insist upon them as we move forward in appointing another member of the judicial branch
column8: and in november if you have the opportunity to transform the legislative branch. #ibelieveher #believewomen

column1: @toocoolformiddleschool says it all and says it well. i sat in a room with two other female teachers yesterday as we traded stories of our own experiences and those of our loved ones. that’s what it is about. it’s not about ruining men or getting justice (though... is justice so wrong?) but about acknowledging and speaking out about what so many females experience on a regular basis. as my friends and i said last night
column2: “who hasn’t at least been made to feel uncomfortable or scared?” something has to change 😤";en;#Repost

column1: this is me at 30. i graduated from uc berkeley with high honors
column3: was with me. this was a joyful moment for me
column4: but my smile acted as a mask for my pain.  while an undergraduate at uc berkeley i was stalked
column6: and assaulted by my then boyfriend; a ph.d. candidate in the anthropology department.

column1: when i reported him for abuse and spoke out against him
column2: i was met with the ""ol' boys club"" closing ranks and doing all that they could to silence me.  my university did not come to my side
column3: the police at campus did not take my statements nor believe me when i shared my story. •

column1: a few years later the man that assaulted me assaulted another woman- this time she was one of his students. it was then that the uc berkeley police came to me to reopen my assault case. at least two other women came forward to report him but nothing came of this
column2: the statue of limitations had run out
column3: and we were left with our trauma
column4: freshly revisited. to this day this assailant is listed as a graduate student in the ph.d. program.

column1: yesterday we witnessed a brave survivor dig into her darkest memories and place them at the feet of an altar of white men. men that hold power over what happens next. men that will show us how serious they take sexual assault in this country. men that are not trauma informed investigators
column2: that are not trained in the nuances of trauma and how it impacts the memory and /or mind. whatever the outcome

column3: trauma lives in the body far beyond the initial incident(s). take good care of you. up your self-care
column5: and love yourself fiercely. we need your light in this darkness
column6: we need you to know just how much you matter.

column1: 331917;instagram;2018-09-28 11:17:01;FALSE;"my fingers are trembling as i post this.

i’ve pushed it down and hidden it away and felt so much shame for so many years. i was a wild teenager. i broke the rules. i kissed too many boys and i thought that fact alone meant i must have deserved what happened. i drank too much. i thought i was invincible. i wasn’t invincible. what happened changed the course of my life. i lost friends because it’s easier to believe that one of your friends is a liar than that another one of your friends is a rapist. but he was a rapist.

after i met my husband- who i am certain was a gift from god- i began to heal. my life has been nothing sort of perfect by the world’s standards. but i have always had the shame just below the surface. i’ve worked so hard to have a perfect family with a perfect little home all the while following every single rule so maybe everyone will see that i am good and that i am no longer the wild
column2: rule breaking teenager that i once was. that everyone who thought i was bad would realize they were wrong. but- i was that girl. and those behaviors as a kid don’t define me. they don’t make me any less good and i owe it to my daughters to stand up to fear.

column1: i was assaulted by a group of boys in high school- some of whom grew up to become terrible men and continued their behaviors with others *one is now a police officer* i lost all my friends and even the parents in my community shunned me.
it was quite traumatic and anyone from my high school days remembers and knows what i’m talking about even today.
i’ve always had such a passion for women’s issues- even before that night in high school- and it’s affected the work i do every day.
now my graduate thesis is a non fictional theatre piece on the #metoo movement. with brett kavanaughs hearing
column3: and even family members saying things like “don’t ruin his life” it’s incredible the amount of change we need in our culture.

column1: it took me telling my friend about that day to realize what had happened wasn't okay. i waited too long and knew that my story wouldn't stand a chance.
because i was ""dating"" the guy who raped me and thought it was my fault for getting myself in that situation. he was 10 years older than me and figured i was just being naive about it all.

column2: hadn't had an actual adult relationship
column3: and thought that when you're dating someone you let them take/do what they want whether you're for it or not. be a ""good girlfriend"". because he was moving out of the country a month and a half later so ""what would be the point""? i wasn't drunk at a party wearing revealing clothes. it was a saturday afternoon around 2:30pm. all i wanted to do was take a shower at the house of the guy i was seeing. he had other plans.

column1: i still get timid (for a split second) when i see a bathroom sink and someone i'm dating comes up behind me because for a split second i fear it's going to happen all over again. i still felt my heart drop when i saw a lookalike board the plane i was working. i still stop dead in my tracks when his face pops up on ""people you may know"". i still cry when i hear other people's stories that are close to me.

i've written about this before but it needs to be said again. my story isn't one of the ""typical"" horrific stories but it's terrifying none the less. i've grown through it. it's broadened my view on so many things. i've learned a lot about myself in the process. am i glad it happened? absolutely not but am i glad for the lessons i learned about myself? you bet. i found strength  i didn't know i had. it's sad but unifying to see when you share your story
column2: you realize how many others have had a similar situation. that loneliness starts to fade really quick. with everything happening lately (and it seems to be more often than not these days) we need to speak up.

column1: 331973;instagram;2018-09-28 11:43:37;FALSE;"i’m not saying kavanaugh is guilty or innocent. that’s not the point of this post. what is the point is this - we cannot create a society that prevents victims from coming forward and then criticize them when they finally muster enough strength years later. we cannot openly believe victims who accuse catholic clergy or a gymnastics doctor years later and say that we understand how difficult it must have been to speak up when it was occurring but then destroy the lives of other victims who speak up against movie stars
column4: and other celebrities. sexual predators often use their power and position and influence as the weapon to subdue and control their victims. it usually takes years for a victim to free themselves of that control before they will speak up
column5: not to mention overcome the shame and misplaced guilt
column6: so stop making it harder for victims to speak up. stop perpetuating an environment that keeps victims silent. •

column1: my coworker and i decides to go out a friday night in 2011. since we are going to work together the next day
column2: we might as well both be hungover.. we buy a bottle of vodka and some fizzy drinks and divide it between us. before we even got the town
column3: i’m too drunk to remember anything.. apparently we end up at a club
column4: where i’m getting kicked out for throwing up on the dance floor (i’m intoxicated beyond what’s healthy) .. my coworker is in line to get our coats
column5: and has instructed me in waiting for her outside. but i don’t .. i walk.. and walk.

column1: the cold air clear up my head a bit
column2: and i find myself at a busstop.. my phone is broken
column3: so i can’t hear what people are saying
column4: but people hears me.. my coworkers phone has run out of money (yes
column5: back then that was a thing
column6: and non of the phones had internet) so we couldn’t communicate.

column1: in my coat i have my keys to my apartment
column2: and since i just left i didn’t get my coat..

column1: at the busstop there’s some helpful people who let me borrow their phone.. but i’m so drunk that i can’t call or use the phone .. i remember about a guy i met on a night out a couple a weeks ago
column2: and we have been in contact since then
column3: but only as friends.  he lives close by
column4: so maybe his home.. i make the people at the busstop call him

column3: didn’t want to say anything because they felt sorry for the man
column4: or maybe just thought they had done something to initiate it unintentionally even when they didn’t. my mum experienced it as did i and we shouldn’t have.

column1: when i was about 15 years old in florida i remember clearly an old man who was a holocaust survivor and a good friend of my parents try to stick his tongue down my throat and french kiss me!  i can’t remember his name or exactly when it happened but i do remember where and how in detail.  i remember i told my family after he’d gone and none of us ever said anything to his wife or even him because of what he had endured in the war
column2: he and his wife had both miraculously survived auschwitz.

column1: i remember hiding the two subsequent days he came round hoping to see if i was there and my mum saying i was out with my older sister who was hiding with me.  my mum
column2: sister and i couldn’t believe his “brass neck” and we were embarrassed not him!
